le]]; grandfather-in-law of Brigadier General [[Willard Ames Holbrook, Jr.]]; son-in-law of Brigadier General [[René Edward De Russy]] |ref=<ref name="hoyle">{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/edhoyle.htm|title=Eli D. Hoyle|publisher=Arlington Cemetery.net|accessdate=2010-08-20}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Hugh L. |last=Scott |year=1876 |nota=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]; [[Indian Wars]]; Superintendent of the [[United States Military Academy]]; Chief of Staff; U.S. Secretary of War; the Navy vessel [[USS Hugh L. Scott (AP-43)]] was named for him |ref=<ref name="scott">{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/hlscott.htm|title=Hugh L. Scott|publisher=Arlington Cemetery.net|accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Eben |last=Swift |year=1876 |nota=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]; [[Spanish–American War]], [[Pancho Villa Expedition]]; commander of the [[82nd Airborne Division|82nd Division]]; Director of the [[United States Army War College]]; commander of [[Camp Gordon]]; commander of U.S. Forces in [[Italy]]; father of Major General [[Innis P. Swift]]; father-in-law of Brigadier General [[Evan Harris Humphrey]]; son-in-law of Brigadier General [[Innis N. Palmer]]; [[Camp Swift, Texas]] is named for him |ref=<ref name="swift">{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/eben-swift.htm|title=Eben Swift|publisher=Arlington Cemetery.net|accessdate=2010-08-21}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Hunter <!--- Also listed in "Indian Wars" and "Spanish-American War and Philippine Insurrection combatants" ---> |last=Liggett |year=1879 |nota=[[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]; [[Indian Wars]]; [[Spanish–American War]]; [[Philippine–American War]]; in 1914 predicted that an invasion of the [[Philippines]] would occur through the [[Lingayen Gulf]], which occurred twice in [[World War II]]; division and corps commander in [[World War I]] |ref=<ref name="liggett">{{cite web|url=http://www.liggett.army.mil/sites/about/history.asp |title=History of Fort Hunter Liggett |date=29 December 2009 |publisher=United States Army Installation Command |accessdate=2010-03-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127114450/http://www.liggett.army.mil/sites/about/history.asp |archivedate=27 January 2010 }}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Benjamin |last=Alvord, Jr. |year=1880 |nota=[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]; Adjutant General of the [[American Expeditionary Force]]; son of Brigadier General [[Benjamin Alvord (mathematician)|Benjamin Alvord]] |ref=<ref name="alvord">{{cite web|url=http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/benjamin-alvordjr.htm|title=Benjamin Alvord, Jr.|publisher=Arlington Cemetery.net|accessdate=2010-03-22}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Richard Whitehead |last=Young |year=1882 |nota=[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]; [[Philippine–American War]]; brigade commander; Justice of the [[Philippines]] Supreme Court; grandson of [[Utah Territory]] Governor [[Brigham Young]] |ref=<ref name="young">{{cite web|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/utah_chapters/statehood_and_the_progressive_era/captainrichardwyoungandspanish-americanwar.html|title=Richard Whitehead Young|publisher=Utah History to Go|accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=John Wilson |last=Ruckman |year=1883 |nota=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]; inventor of artillery devices; commander of [[Fort Baker]] and [[Fort Mills]]; commander of the Southeastern Department (Aug 1917) Southern Department (Sept 1917) and the Northeastern Department (May 1918) |ref=<ref name="ruckman">{{cite web|url=http://psruckman.com/JWR.htm|title=John Wilson Ruckman|publisher=PS Ruckman.com|accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref>}} {{mem/a2 |first=Edwin Burr |last=Babbitt |year=1884 |nota=[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]; [[Meuse-Argonne Offensive]], [[Battle of Saint-Mihiel]]; recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Med